Environment-climate: for a European New Deal
BRUSSELS – In Brussels as in European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on every tongue, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
But this time, it is about the environment and climate.
And Europe is the continent where we can and must act.
The European Union's commitment to these issues is not new: we have had a common program since 1972.
Later in 2005, the EU established the first emissions trading system, which remains the world's first CO2 market.
And in 2015, the EU played a leading role in negotiating the Paris Agreement, committing to reduce its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (base: 1990 levels).
But these measures, although significant, are not sufficient to address the challenges facing today's world.
Increasingly high temperatures could lead to the complete disappearance of Arctic sea ice by 2050.
Bees and many other insects are dying out, while microplastic pollution is ubiquitous in our environment.
And the number of victims of respiratory diseases is increasing as air pollution worsens.
We nevertheless have reasons to remain optimistic.
Let us look at these people, growing in number every day, ready to act to question their lifestyles. Take these students and entire families descending into the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
Companies are also committing themselves, seeing the unmatched economic potential of a green economy.
But it is the politicians and policymakers, at the national and European levels, who too often lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Let's seize it!
And let us make a green Europe our first political priority for the years ahead, focused on three key areas.
Firstly, the EU must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit global warming to 1.5°C, we have no other choice: the EU's net carbon dioxide emissions must be reduced to zero by mid-century.
Together, we can invest massively in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings, renewable energies, as well as in key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, new generations of solar panels, and green chemistry.
We must also apply strict CO2 emission limits to new private cars, public transport, and commercial maritime and air transport.
And, by working closely with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the leading continent for electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a leading role in the responsible use of resources and become a true circular economy that is waste-efficient.
Every year, 8 billion tonnes of materials are transformed into energy or products in the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tonnes come from recycling.
We must do much better, which will require us to focus on four areas: food waste and the bioeconomy, textiles, construction, and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let's get to work right away, by launching, for example, an EU initiative to combat planned obsolescence of household appliances and electronic devices, and by eliminating plastics from our value chains.
Thirdly, we must do much more to protect biodiversity.
According to the WWF, wild species populations have decreased by about 60% worldwide since 1970.
The UN Biodiversity Conference, which will take place in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must show the way.
We must strengthen the EU's legislation on species protection and put forward an ambitious plan for the blue economy and the preservation of our seas.
We must also launch a genuine debate with our farmers (not against them!) on the revision of our standards and the modernization of the common agricultural policy to support this green transition.
But these massive tasks that await us, we will not be able to accomplish them if it is always the same – and the most vulnerable – who are asked to bear the costs.
All measures under consideration must therefore first and foremost be designed to minimize social costs.
And in parallel, we must today work with our partners for international cooperation, fighting against unfair competition.
Because it is pointless to have strict European rules on pesticides or forest management if our imported food and timber are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three initiatives could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the EU's new political cycle.
Because we are in an acute ecological debt situation, and it would be more than justified that the stability and growth pact applying to the public finances of the Member States find an equivalent for environmental objectives!
To achieve its goals, this Sustainability Pact will require concerted action in all areas: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not hesitate to use its regulatory powers, for example: expanding the scope of legislation on eco-design and the "extended producer responsibility" for products placed on the market could significantly stimulate environmental innovation.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros in investments each year to meet the commitments made under the Paris Agreement.
This is a feasible objective.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral actor providing climate-focused funding.
And the new EU budget and its investment plan, making the best use of private sector investments, could further strengthen the Union's capacity for action.
The financial sector must play a fundamental role: through the disclosure of climate-related financial information, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as the Norwegian sovereign fund and BlackRock, to adopt a long-term vision and avoid what the governor of the Bank of England, Mark Carney, called the "tragedy of the horizon."
Finally, although some member states may see this as a risky project, we must have a debate on taxation, as well as on subsidies applicable to fossil fuels. In short, on the integration of sustainability into public spending.
Behind these projects, these initiatives, the key lies in the method. For this "Green New Deal" to bear fruit, we must set ambitious targets and "missions" for the short and long term that have real societal resonance.
With the member states and the European Parliament, we will have to determine a common roadmap and carry out in-depth discussions, just as with our regions, cities, businesses, trade unions, and civil society.
Tout cela ne peut pas être fait du jour au lendemain.
Mais nous ne pouvons plus fermer les yeux et retenir notre respiration pour échapper à la réalité de notre environnement.
Il est déjà très tard pour lancer un « Green New Deal » européen. Mais il n’est pas trop tard.
Ne ratons pas cette nouvelle opportunité !
